ter of a [[pin]]head\n* 1.5&nbsp;mm \u2014 length of average [[flea]]\n* 2.54&nbsp;mm \u2014 distance between pins on old [[dual in-line package|DIP]] (dual-inline-package) electronic components \n* 5&nbsp;mm \u2014 length of average red [[ant]]\n* [[5.56\u00d745mm NATO]] \u2014 standard ammunition size\n* [[7.62\u00d751mm NATO]] \u2014 common military ammunition size\n\n==1 centimeter==\n{{Orders of magnitude (length) imagemap human-scale}}\nLengths between 10<sup>\u22122</sup> and 10<sup>\u22121</sup>&nbsp;m (1and 10&nbsp;[[centimetre|cm]]).\n\n* 1&nbsp;cm \u2014 10 [[millimetre]]s\n* 1&nbsp;cm \u2014 0.39 [[inch]]es\n* 1&nbsp;cm \u2014 edge of [[square (geometry)|square]] of area [[Orders of magnitude (area)|1&nbsp;cm<sup>2</sup>]]\n* 1&nbsp;cm \u2014 edge of [[cube (geometry)|cube]] of volume [[Orders of magnitude (one cubic millimetre to one cubic metre)|1&nbsp;ml]]\n* 1&nbsp;cm \u2014 approximate width of average [[fingernail]]\n* 1.5&nbsp;cm \u2014 length of a very large [[mosquito]]\n* 2&nbsp;cm \u2014 approximate width of an adult human [[finger]]\n* 2.54&nbsp;cm \u2014 1 [[inch]]\n* 3.1&nbsp;cm \u2014 1 [[attoparsec]] (10<sup>\u221218</sup> [[parsec]]s)\n* 3.5&nbsp;cm \u2014 width of film commonly used in [[motion pictures]] and [[photographic film|still photography]]\n* 4.3&nbsp;cm \u2014 minimum diameter of a [[golf]] ball<ref>{{cite web |title= USGA: Guide to the Rules on Clubs and Balls |url= http://www.usga.org/Rule-Books/Rules-on-Clubs-and-Balls/Appendix-III-%e2%80%93-The-Ball/ |publisher= USGA |accessdate=2011-09-30}}</ref>\n* 7.3-7.5&nbsp;cm \u2014 diameter of a [[baseball]]<!-- Calculated from requirement that the circumference be 9 to 9.25 inches:  9*2.54/pi = 7.3e-2m.  9.25*2.54/pi = 7.5e-2m --><ref>{{cite web |title= Official Rules |url= http://mlb.mlb.com/mlb/official_info/official_rules/objectives_1.jsp |publisher= MLB |accessdate=2011-09-30}}</ref>\n* 8.6&nbsp;cm \u00d7 5.4&nbsp;cm \u2014 dimensions of a typical [[credit card]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dimensionsguide.com/credit-card-dimensions/ |title=Credit Card Dimensions |accessdate=2011-09-30 }}</ref>\n\n==1 decimetre==\nLengths between 10 and 100 centimetres (10<sup>\u22121</sup> and 1&nbsp;metre).\n\n===Conversions===\n10 centimetres (abbreviated to 10&nbsp;cm) is equal to\n* 1 [[decimetre]] (dm), a term not in common use\n* 100 [[millimetre]]s\n* 3.9 [[inch]]es\n* A side of a [[Square (geometry)|square]] of area [[Orders of magnitude (area)|0.01&nbsp;m<sub>2</sub>]] <ref name=\"abbr\" group=note>''m'' is an abbreviation of metre; ''cm'' of centimetre; ''dm'' of decimetre; ''m<sup>2</sup>'' is short for [[square metre]]; ''m<sup>3</sup>'' is short for [[cubic metre]]</ref>\n* The edge of a [[cube (geometry)|cube]] with a volume of [[Orders of magnitude (one cubic millimetre to one cubic metre)|{{val|1|e=-3|u=m3}}]]<ref name=\"abbr\" group=note/> (one [[litre]])\n\n===Wavelengths===\n*10&nbsp;cm = 1.0 dm<ref name=\"abbr\" group=note/> \u2013 wavelength of the highest [[ultra high frequency|UHF]] radio frequency, [[picosecond|3 GHz]]\n*12&nbsp;cm = 1.2 dm \u2013 wavelength of the [[ISM band|2.45 GHz ISM radio band]]\n*21&nbsp;cm = 2.1 dm \u2013 wavelength of the [[21 cm line|1.4 GHz hydrogen emission line]], a [[hyperfine structure|hyperfine]] transition of the hydrogen atom\n*100&nbsp;cm = 10 dm \u2013 wavelength of the lowest [[ultra high frequency|UHF]] radio frequency, [[nanosecond|300 MHz]]\n\n===Human-defined scales and structures===\n\n* 10.16&nbsp;cm = 1.016 dm \u2014 1 hand used in measuring height of horses (4&nbsp;inches)\n* 12&nbsp;cm = 1.2 dm \u2014 diameter of a [[Compact Disc]] (CD) (= 120&nbsp;mm)\n* 15&nbsp;cm = 1.5 dm \u2014 length of a [[Bic pen]] with cap on\n* 22&nbsp;cm = 2.2 dm \u2014 diameter of a typical [[soccer ball]]\n* 30.48&nbsp;cm = 3.048 dm \u2014 1 [[foot (length)|foot]]\n* 30&nbsp;cm = 3 dm \u2014 typical school-use [[ruler]] length (= 300&nbsp;mm)\n* 60&nbsp;cm = 6 dm \u2014 standard depth (front to back) of a domestic kitchen worktop in Europe (= 600&nbsp;mm)\n* 90&nbsp;cm = 9 dm \u2014 average length of a [[rapier]], a [[fencing]] sword<ref>http://www.2-clicks-swords.com/article/what-is-a-rapier.html</ref>\n* 91.44&nbsp;cm = 9.144 dm \u2014 one [[yard]]\n* [[Cigarette]]s 100&nbsp;mm (4&nbsp;in) in length\n\n===Nature===\n\n* {{citation needed span|text=10&nbsp;cm = 1 dm \u2014 diameter of the human [[cervix]] upon entering the second stage of [[childbirth|labour]]|date=June 2011}}\n* {{citation needed span|text=15&nbsp;cm = 1.5 dm \u2014 approximate size of largest [[Titanus giganteus|beetle]] species|date=February 2009}}\n* {{citation needed span|text=29&nbsp;cm = 2.9 dm \u2014 length of average human [[foot]]|date=July 2009|reason=Also, are we only considering adult men or also adult women?}}\n* 29.98&nbsp;cm = distance light travels in one [[nanosecond]]\n* {{citation needed span|text=31&nbsp;cm = 3.1 dm \u2014 wingspan of largest [[butterfly]] species [[Queen Alexandra's birdwing|''Ornithoptera alexandrae'']]|date=February 2009}}\n* {{citation needed span|text=50 to 65&nbsp;cm \u2014 a [[pizote]]'s tail|date=February 2009}}\n* 66&nbsp;cm \u2014 length of the longest [[pine]] cones (produced by the [[sugar pine]]<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.na.fs.fed.us/Spfo/pubs/silvics_manual/Volume_1/pinus/lambertiana.htm | title=Pinus lambertiana |author1=Bohun B. Kinloch, Jr.  |author2=William H. Scheuner  |lastauthoramp=yes| accessdate=8 June 2011| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110608015717/http://www.na.fs.fed.us/Spfo/pubs/silvics_manual/Volume_1/pinus/lambertiana.htm| archivedate= 8 June 2011 | url-status= live}}</ref>)\n\n==Longer==\n#[[1 metre]]\n# [[1 decametre]]\n# [[1 hectometre]]\n# [[1 kilometre]]\n# [[1 myriametre]]\n# [[100 kilometres]]\n# [[1 megametre]]\n# [[10 megametres]]\n# [[100 megametres]]\n\n==1 gigametre==\n{{Orders of magnitude (length) imagemap astronomical-scale}}\n[[Image:1e9m comparison.png|thumb|350px|right|Upper part: [[Gamma Orionis]], [[Algol|Algol B]], the [[Sun]] (centre), underneath their darker mirror images <span style=\"white-space:nowrap;\">(artist's interpretation),</span> and <span style=\"white-space:nowrap;\">[[100 megametres|other objects]],</span> to scale.]]\nLengths starting at 10<sup>9</sup> metres (1 [[gigametre]] (Gm) or 1 million kilometres).\n\n'''[[100 megametres|Distances shorter than 10<sup>9</sup> metres]]'''\n* 1.4 Gm &mdash; Diameter of [[Sun]]<ref>[http://nssdc.gsfc.nasa.gov/planetary/factsheet/sunfact.html Sun Fact Sheet]</ref>\n* 1.5 Gm &mdash; ''(proposed) Expected orbit from Earth of the [[James Webb Space Telescope]]''\n* 2.19 Gm &mdash; Closest approach of [[Comet Lexell]] to [[Earth]], happened on 1 July 1770; closest [[comet]] approach on record\n* 3 Gm &mdash; Total length of \"wiring\" in the human brain.<ref>Neuroscience: The Science of the Brain {{cite web|url=http://www.braincampaign.org/Pub/Pub_Main_Display.asp?LC_Docs_ID%3D2769 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-06-08 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110202081347/http://www.braincampaign.org/Pub/Pub_Main_Display.asp?LC_Docs_ID=2769 |archivedate=2011-02-02 }} p.44</ref>\n* 4.2 Gm &mdash; Diameter of [[Algol|Algol B]]\n* 5.0 Gm &mdash; Closest approach of [[Comet Halley]] to Earth, happened on 10 April 837\n* ''5.0 Gm &mdash; (proposed) Size of the arms of the giant triangle shaped Michelson interferometer of the [[Laser Interferometer Space Antenna]] (LISA) planned to start observations in or around 2015.''\n* 7.9 Gm &mdash; Diameter of [[Gamma Orionis]]\n* 9.0 Gm &mdash; Estimated diameter of the [[event horizon]] of [[Sagittarius A*]], the [[supermassive black hole]] in the center of the [[Milky Way]] galaxy\n\n==Longer==\n# [[10 gigametres]]\n# [[100 gigametres]]\n# [[1 terametre]]\n# [[10 terametres]]\n# [[100 terametres]]\n# [[1 petametre]]\n# [[10 petametres]]\n# [[100 petametres]]\n# [[1 exametre]]\n# [[10 exametres]]\n# [[100 exametres]]\n# [[1 zettametre]]\n# [[10 zettametres]]\n# [[100 zettametres]]\n# [[1 yottametre]]\n# [[10 yottametres]]\n# [[100 yottametres]]\n# [[1 kilometer]]\n# [[1 MegaMameter|MegaMameter]] (MMm)\n\n==See also==\n*[[Length]]\n*[[Orders of magnitude (length)]] <!-- should be merged -->\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n[[Category:Length|*]]\n", "text_old": "{{main|Orders of magnitude (length)}}\n\n[[File:Size planets comparison.jpg|thumb|right|Planets of the Solar System to scale]]\n\nThis is a '''list of examples of lengths''', in metres in order to give an understanding of [[length]]s.\n{{TOC right}}\n\n== Shorter than 1 ym ==\n\n* {{val|1.62|e=-35}} metres = the [[Planck length]]\n\n== 1 ym to 1 zm ==\n\n* {{val|1|e=-24}} metres = 1&nbsp;ym = 1 [[metre#SI prefixed forms of metre|yoctometre]], the smallest named subdivision of the metre in the [[International System of Units|SI]] [[SI base unit|base unit]] of length.\n* {{val|1|e=-23}} metres = 10&nbsp;ym\n* {{val|2|e=-23}} metres = 20&nbsp;ym, the effective cross-section radius of 1 [[MeV]] [[neutrino]]s as measured by [[Clyde Cowan]] and [[Frederick Reines]]<ref>{{cite web |author=Carl R. Nave |url=http://hyperphysics.phy-astr.gsu.edu/hbase/particles/cowan.html#c1 |title=Cowan and Reines Neutrino Experiment |accessdate=2008-12-04}} ({{val|6.3|e=-44|u=cm2}}, which gives an effective radius of about {{val|2|e=-23|u=m}})</ref>\n\n== 1 zm to 1 am ==\n\n* {{val|1|e=-21}} metres = 1 zm = 1 [[metre#SI prefixed forms of metre|zeptometre]] = {{val|1000}} [[metre#SI prefixed forms of metre|yoctometre]]s\n* {{val|2|e=-21}} metres = radius of effective [[Cross section (physics)|cross section]] for a [[Orders of magnitude (energy)#1E-9|20]] [[GeV]] [[neutrino]] scattering off a [[nucleon]]<ref name=\"NaveN3\">{{cite web |author=Carl R. Nave |url=http://hyperphysics.phy-astr.gsu.edu/hbase/particles/neutrino3.html#c2 |title=Neutron Absorption Cross-sections |accessdate=2008-12-04}} (area for 20 GeV about {{val|1|e=-41|u=m2}} gives effective radius of about {{val|2|e=-21|u=m}}; for 250&nbsp;GeV about {{val|1.5|e=-40|u=m2}} gives effective radius of about {{val|7|e=-21|u=m}})</ref>\n* {{val|7|e=-21}} metres = radius of effective cross section for a [[Orders of magnitude (energy)#1E-9|250]] GeV neutrino scattering off a nucleon<ref name=\"NaveN3\"/>\n* {{val|1|e=-20}} metres = 10&nbsp;zm\n* {{val|1|e=-19}} metres = 100&nbsp;zm\n* 310&nbsp;zm \u2014 [[de Broglie wavelength]] of [[protons]] at the [[Large Hadron Collider]] (4&nbsp;TeV as of 2012)\n\n== 1 am to 1 fm ==\n\n* {{val|1|e=-18}} metres = 1&nbsp;am = 1 [[metre#SI prefixed forms of metre|attometre]] = {{val|1000}} [[metre#SI prefixed forms of metre|zeptometres]]\n* 1&nbsp;am \u2014 sensitivity of the [[LIGO]] detector for [[gravitational wave]]s\n* {{val|1|e=-17}} metres = 10&nbsp;am\n* {{val|1|e=-16}} metres = 100 am\n* 0.85&nbsp;fm \u2014 approximate proton radius<ref>{{cite journal |doi= 10.1038/nature09250 |title= The size of the proton |author1=Randolf Pohl |author2=Aldo Antognini |author3=Fran\u00e7ois Nez |author4=Fernando D. Amaro |author5=Fran\u00e7ois Biraben |author6=Jo\u00e3o M. R. Cardoso |author7=Daniel S. Covita |author8=Andreas Dax |author9=Satish Dhawan |author10=Luis M. P. Fernandes |author11=Adolf Giesen |author12=Thomas Graf |author13=Theodor W. H\u00e4nsch |author14=Paul Indelicato |author15=Lucile Julien |author16=Cheng-Yang Kao |author17=Paul Knowles |author18=Eric-Olivier Le Bigot |author19=Yi-Wei Liu |author20=Jos\u00e9 A. M. Lopes |author21=Livia Ludhova |author22=Cristina M. B. Monteiro |author23=Fran\u00e7oise Mulhauser |author24=Tobias Nebel |author25=Paul Rabinowitz |display-authors =etal |date= 8 July 2010|journal=Nature |volume=466 |issue= 7303 |pages =213\u2013216 |pmid= 20613837 |bibcode=2010Natur.466..213P|url= https://rdcu.be/bYa2m }}</ref>\n\n== 1 fm to 1 pm ==\n\n* {{val|1|e=-15}} metres = 1&nbsp;fm = 1 [[metre#SI prefixed forms of metre|femtometre]] = {{val|1000}} [[metre#SI prefixed forms of metre|attometres]]\n* 1.5&nbsp;fm \u2014 diameter of the [[Cross section (physics)|Scattering Cross Section]] of an 11 [[Electron volt|MeV]] [[proton]] with a target proton<ref name=\"Nav\"/><!-- To verify, use online form with these figures: Z=1 KE=11 A=1 and obtain cross section of 1.758 fm^2; divide by Pi then square root and double -->\n* {{val|2.81794|u=fm}} \u2014 [[classical electron radius]]<ref>[[National Institute of Standards and Technology|NIST]]. [http://physics.nist.gov/cgi-bin/cuu/Value?re CODATA Value:    classical electron radius]. Retrieved 2009-02-10</ref>\n* 7&nbsp;fm - the radius of the effective scattering [[Cross section (physics)|cross section]] for a gold nucleus scattering a [[Orders of magnitude (energy)#1E-15|6]] [[Electron volt|MeV]] [[alpha particle]] over 140 degrees<ref name=\"Nav\">{{cite web |author=Carl R. Nave |url=http://hyperphysics.phy-astr.gsu.edu/hbase/nuclear/crosec.html |title= Scattering Cross Section |accessdate=2009-02-10}}</ref>\n* {{val|1|e=-14}} metres = 10&nbsp;fm\n* {{val|1|e=-13}} metres = 100&nbsp;fm\n* {{val|1|e=-12}} metres = 1&nbsp;pm = 1 [[metre#SI prefixed forms of metre|picometre]] = {{val|1000}} [[metre#SI prefixed forms of metre|femtometres]]\n\n==1 picometre==\nLengths between 10<sup>\u221212</sup> and 10<sup>\u221211</sup> m (1 and 10&nbsp;[[picometre|pm]]).\n<!--as long as 'femtometre' redirects to 'metre', on next line linking into the latter article to the table-->\n* 1 pm = 1 picometre = {{val|1000}} [[metre#SI prefixed forms of metre|femtometres]]\n* 1 pm = distance between [[atomic nuclei]] in a [[white dwarf star]]\n* 2.4 pm \u2014 The [[Compton wavelength]] of the [[electron]].\n* 5 pm \u2014 shorter [[X-ray]] wavelengths (approx.)\n\n==10 picometres==\nLengths between 10<sup>\u221211</sup> and 10<sup>\u221210</sup>&nbsp;m (10 [[picometre|pm]] and 100 pm).\n* 25 pm \u2014 [[empirical radius]] of [[hydrogen]] [[atom]]<ref name=\"webelhy\">{{cite web |author=Mark Winter |title=WebElements Periodi