help compare different [[orders of magnitude]] this page lists lengths between 10<sup>\u22123</sup> and 10<sup>\u22122</sup> m (1&nbsp;mm and 1&nbsp;cm).\n\n* 1.0&nbsp;mm \u2014 {{sfrac|{{val|1000}}}} of a [[metre]]\n* 1.0&nbsp;mm \u2014 {{val|0.03937}} [[inch]]es or {{frac|5|127}} (exactly)\n* 1.0&nbsp;mm \u2014 side of [[square (geometry)|square]] of area [[Orders of magnitude (area)|1 mm<sup>2</sup>]]\n* 1.0&nbsp;mm \u2014 diameter of a [[pin]]head\n* 1.5&nbsp;mm \u2014 length of average [[flea]]\n* 2.54&nbsp;mm \u2014 distance between pins on old [[dual in-line package|DIP]] (dual-inline-package) electronic components \n* 5&nbsp;mm \u2014 length of average red [[ant]]\n* [[5.56\u00d745mm NATO]] \u2014 standard ammunition size\n* [[7.62\u00d751mm NATO]] \u2014 common military ammunition size\n\n==1 centimeter==\n{{Orders of magnitude (length) imagemap human-scale}}\nLengths between 10<sup>\u22122</sup> and 10<sup>\u22121</sup>&nbsp;m (1and 10&nbsp;[[centimetre|cm]]).\n\n* 1&nbsp;cm \u2014 10 [[millimetre]]s\n* 1&nbsp;cm \u2014 0.39 [[inch]]es\n* 1&nbsp;cm \u2014 edge of [[square (geometry)|square]] of area [[Orders of magnitude (area)|1&nbsp;cm<sup>2</sup>]]\n* 1&nbsp;cm \u2014 edge of [[cube (geometry)|cube]] of volume [[Orders of magnitude (one cubic millimetre to one cubic metre)|1&nbsp;ml]]\n* 1&nbsp;cm \u2014 approximate width of average [[fingernail]]\n* 1.5&nbsp;cm \u2014 length of a very large [[mosquito]]\n* 2&nbsp;cm \u2014 approximate width of an adult human [[finger]]\n* 2.54&nbsp;cm \u2014 1 [[inch]]\n* 3.1&nbsp;cm \u2014 1 [[attoparsec]] (10<sup>\u221218</sup> [[parsec]]s)\n* 3.5&nbsp;cm \u2014 width of film commonly used in [[motion pictures]] and [[photographic film|still photography]]\n* 4.3&nbsp;cm \u2014 minimum diameter of a [[golf]] ball<ref>{{cite web |title= USGA: Guide to the Rules on Clubs and Balls |url= http://www.usga.org/Rule-Books/Rules-on-Clubs-and-Balls/Appendix-III-%e2%80%93-The-Ball/ |publisher= USGA |accessdate=2011-09-30}}</ref>\n* 7.3-7.5&nbsp;cm \u2014 diameter of a [[baseball]]<!-- Calculated from requirement that the circumference be 9 to 9.25 inches:  9*2.54/pi = 7.3e-2m.  9.25*2.54/pi = 7.5e-2m --><ref>{{cite web |title= Official Rules |url= http://mlb.mlb.com/mlb/official_info/official_rules/objectives_1.jsp |publisher= MLB |accessdate=2011-09-30}}</ref>\n* 8.6&nbsp;cm \u00d7 5.4&nbsp;cm \u2014 dimensions of a typical [[credit card]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dimensionsguide.com/credit-card-dimensions/ |title=Credit Card Dimensions |accessdate=2011-09-30 }}</ref>\n\n==1 decimetre==\nLengths between 10 and 100 centimetres (10<sup>\u22121</sup> and 1&nbsp;metre).\n\n===Conversions===\n10 centimetres (abbreviated to 10&nbsp;cm) is equal to\n* 1 [[decimetre]] (dm), a term not in common use\n* 100 [[millimetre]]s\n* 3.9 [[inch]]es\n* A side of a [[Square (geometry)|square]] of area [[Orders of magnitude (area)|0.01&nbsp;m<sub>2</sub>]] <ref name=\"abbr\" group=note>''m'' is an abbreviation of metre; ''cm'' of centimetre; ''dm'' of decimetre; ''m<sup>2</sup>'' is short for [[square metre]]; ''m<sup>3</sup>'' is short for [[cubic metre]]</ref>\n* The edge of a [[cube (geometry)|cube]] with a volume of [[Orders of magnitude (one cubic millimetre to one cubic metre)|{{val|1|e=-3|u=m3}}]]<ref name=\"abbr\" group=note/> (one [[litre]])\n\n===Wavelengths===\n*10&nbsp;cm = 1.0 dm<ref name=\"abbr\" group=note/> \u2013 wavelength of the highest [[ultra high frequency|UHF]] radio frequency, [[picosecond|3 GHz]]\n*12&nbsp;cm = 1.2 dm \u2013 wavelength of the [[ISM band|2.45 GHz ISM radio band]]\n*21&nbsp;cm = 2.1 dm \u2013 wavelength of the [[21 cm line|1.4 GHz hydrogen emission line]], a [[hyperfine structure|hyperfine]] transition of the hydrogen atom\n*100&nbsp;cm = 10 dm \u2013 wavelength of the lowest [[ultra high frequency|UHF]] radio frequency, [[nanosecond|300 MHz]]\n\n===Human-defined scales and structures===\n\n* 10.16&nbsp;cm = 1.016 dm \u2014 1 hand used in measuring height of horses (4&nbsp;inches)\n* 12&nbsp;cm = 1.2 dm \u2014 diameter of a [[Compact Disc]] (CD) (= 120&nbsp;mm)\n* 15&nbsp;cm = 1.5 dm \u2014 length of a [[Bic pen]] with cap on\n* 22&nbsp;cm = 2.2 dm \u2014 diameter of a typical [[soccer ball]]\n* 30.48&nbsp;cm = 3.048 dm \u2014 1 [[foot (length)|foot]]\n* 30&nbsp;cm = 3 dm \u2014 typical school-use [[ruler]] length (= 300&nbsp;mm)\n* 60&nbsp;cm = 6 dm \u2014 standard depth (front to back) of a domestic kitchen worktop in Europe (= 600&nbsp;mm)\n* 90&nbsp;cm = 9 dm \u2014 average length of a [[rapier]], a [[fencing]] sword<ref>http://www.2-clicks-swords.com/article/what-is-a-rapier.html</ref>\n* 91.44&nbsp;cm = 9.144 dm \u2014 one [[yard]]\n* [[Cigarette]]s 100&nbsp;mm (4&nbsp;in) in length\n\n===Nature===\n\n* {{citation needed span|text=10&nbsp;cm = 1 dm \u2014 diameter of the human [[cervix]] upon entering the second stage of [[childbirth|labour]]|date=June 2011}}\n* {{citation needed span|text=15&nbsp;cm = 1.5 dm \u2014 approximate size of largest [[Titanus giganteus|beetle]] species|date=February 2009}}\n* {{citation needed span|text=29&nbsp;cm = 2.9 dm \u2014 length of average human [[foot]]|date=July 2009|reason=Also, are we only considering adult men or also adult women?}}\n* 29.98&nbsp;cm = distance light travels in one [[nanosecond]]\n* {{citation needed span|text=31&nbsp;cm = 3.1 dm \u2014 wingspan of largest [[butterfly]] species [[Queen Alexandra's birdwing|''Ornithoptera alexandrae'']]|date=February 2009}}\n* {{citation needed span|text=50 to 65&nbsp;cm \u2014 a [[pizote]]'s tail|date=February 2009}}\n* 66&nbsp;cm \u2014 length of the longest [[pine]] cones (produced by the [[sugar pine]]<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.na.fs.fed.us/Spfo/pubs/silvics_manual/Volume_1/pinus/lambertiana.htm | title=Pinus lambertiana |author1=Bohun B. Kinloch, Jr.  |author2=William H. Scheuner  |lastauthoramp=yes| accessdate=8 June 2011| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110608015717/http://www.na.fs.fed.us/Spfo/pubs/silvics_manual/Volume_1/pinus/lambertiana.htm| archivedate= 8 June 2011 | url-status= live}}</ref>)\n\n==Longer==\n#[[1 metre]]\n# [[1 decametre]]\n# [[1 hectometre]]\n# [[1 kilometre]]\n# [[1 myriametre]]\n# [[100 kilometres]]\n# [[1 megametre]]\n# [[10 megametres]]\n# [[100 megametres]]\n\n==1 gigametre==\n{{Orders of magnitude (length) imagemap astronomical-scale}}\n[[Image:1e9m comparison.png|thumb|350px|right|Upper part: [[Gamma Orionis]], [[Algol|Algol B]], the [[Sun]] (centre), underneath their darker mirror images <span style=\"white-space:nowrap;\">(artist's interpretation),</span> and <span style=\"white-space:nowrap;\">[[100 megametres|other objects]],</span> to scale.]]\nLengths starting at 10<sup>9</sup> metres (1 [[gigametre]] (Gm) or 1 million kilometres).\n\n'''[[100 megametres|Distances shorter than 10<sup>9</sup> metres]]'''\n* 1.4 Gm &mdash; Diameter of [[Sun]]<ref>[http://nssdc.gsfc.nasa.gov/planetary/factsheet/sunfact.html Sun Fact Sheet]</ref>\n* 1.5 Gm &mdash; ''(proposed) Expected orbit from Earth of the [[James Webb Space Telescope]]''\n* 2.19 Gm &mdash; Closest approach of [[Comet Lexell]] to [[Earth]], happened on 1 July 1770; closest [[comet]] approach on record\n* 3 Gm &mdash; Total length of \"wiring\" in the human brain.<ref>Neuroscience: The Science of the Brain {{cite web|url=http://www.braincampaign.org/Pub/Pub_Main_Display.asp?LC_Docs_ID%3D2769 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-06-08 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110202081347/http://www.braincampaign.org/Pub/Pub_Main_Display.asp?LC_Docs_ID=2769 |archivedate=2011-02-02 }} p.44</ref>\n* 4.2 Gm &mdash; Diameter of [[Algol|Algol B]]\n* 5.0 Gm &mdash; Closest approach of [[Comet Halley]] to Earth, happened on 10 April 837\n* ''5.0 Gm &mdash; (proposed) Size of the arms of the giant triangle shaped Michelson interferometer of the [[Laser Interferometer Space Antenna]] (LISA) planned to start observations in or around 2015.''\n* 7.9 Gm &mdash; Diameter of [[Gamma Orionis]]\n* 9.0 Gm &mdash; Estimated diameter of the [[event horizon]] of [[Sagittarius A*]], the [[supermassive black hole]] in the center of the [[Milky Way]] galaxy\n\n==Longer==\n# [[10 gigametres]]\n# [[100 gigametres]]\n# [[1 terametre]]\n# [[10 terametres]]\n# [[100 terametres]]\n# [[1 petametre]]\n# [[10 petametres]]\n# [[100 petametres]]\n# [[1 exametre]]\n# [[10 exametres]]\n# [[100 exametres]]\n# [[1 zettametre]]\n# [[10 zettametres]]\n# [[100 zettametres]]\n# [[1 yottametre]]\n# [[10 yottametres]]\n# [[100 yottametres]]\n# [[1 kilometer]]\n# [[1 MegaMameter|MegaMameter]] (MMm)\n\n==See also==\n*[[Length]]\n*[[Orders of magnitude (length)]] <!-- should be merged -->\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n[[Category:Length|*]]\n", "name_user": "Nemo bis", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(remove broken link)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_examples_of_lengths"}
{"title_page": "Travel restrictions related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic", "text_new": "{{about|international travel restrictions|domestic travel restrictions and lockdowns|National responses to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{short description|Restrictions by countries intended to stop spread of disease}}\n{{Current disaster|event=pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{expand list|date=March 2020}}\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic sidebar|expanded=issues}}[[File:COVID-19 Outbreak World Map-GlobalTravelBan.svg|thumb|495x495px|Some of the countries that have imposed a global travel ban in response to the COVID-19 pandemic, as of April 5, 2020 {{legend|firebrick|Current ban on foreign travellers}}{{legend|blue|Former ban on foreign travellers}}]]\n\nAs a result of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|<noinclude>2019\u201320 coronavirus </noinclude>pandemic]], many countries and regions have imposed quarantines, entry bans, or other restrictions for citizens of or recent travellers to the most affected areas.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/article/coronavirus-travel-restrictions.html|title=Coronavirus Travel Restrictions, Across the Globe|date=26 March 2020|work=The New York Times}}</ref> Other countries and regions have imposed global restrictions that apply to all foreign countries and territories, or prevent their own citizens from travelling overseas.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.smartraveller.gov.au/COVID-19-australian-travellers|title=Coronavirus (COVID-19) \u2013 information for Australian travellers|date=April 9, 2020|publisher=Australian Government}}</ref>\n\nTogether with a decreased willingness to travel, the restrictions have had a [[socio-economic impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|negative economic and social impact]] on the travel sector in those regions. A possible long-term impact has been a decline of [[business travel]] and international conferencing, and the rise of their virtual, online equivalents.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jpost.com/Opinion/The-long-term-effects-of-the-coronavirus-619118|title=The long-term effects of the coronavirus|website=The Jerusalem Post {{!}} JPost.com|access-date=2020-03-12}}</ref> Concerns have been raised over the effectiveness of travel restrictions to contain the spread of [[COVID-19]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Nsikan |first1=Akpan |title=Coronavirus spikes outside China show travel bans aren\u2019t working |url=https://www.nationalgeographic.com/science/2020/02/why-travel-restrictions-are-not-stopping-coronavirus-covid-19/ |accessdate=2 April 2020 |work=National Geographic |date=24 February 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe [[European Union]] rejected the idea of suspending the [[Schengen Agreement|Schengen free travel zone]] and introducing border controls with Italy,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.dw.com/en/coronavirus-eu-rules-out-schengen-border-closures-amid-italy-outbreak/a-52497811|title=Coronavirus: EU rules out Schengen border closures amid Italy outbreak|date=24 February 2020|publisher=Deutsche Welle}}</ref> a decision which has been [[Criticism of response to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|criticized]] by some European politicians.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/diplomacy/article/3073897/coronavirus-european-borders-likely-remain-open-despite-crisis|title=Coronavirus: European borders likely to remain open despite crisis in Italy, observers say|date=7 March 2020|work=[[South China Morning Post]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/26/world/europe/coronavirus-european-union.html|title=Coronavirus Nightmare Could Be the End for Europe's Borderless Dream|date=26 February 2020|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> After some EU member states announced complete closure of their national borders to foreign nationals,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/tamarathiessen/2020/03/14/coronavirus-europe-closes-borders-tourists/|title=Coronavirus: Some Of These 24 European Countries Have Closed Their Borders To Tourists|date=14 March 2020|work=[[Forbes]]}}</ref> the [[European Commission]] President [[Ursula von der Leyen]] said that \"Certain controls may be justified, but general travel bans are not seen as being the most effective by the World Health Organization.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ft.com/content/4e89ec5c-6565-11ea-b3f3-fe4680ea68b5|title=Denmark, Poland and Czechs seal borders over coronavirus|date=12 March 2020|work=Financial Times}}</ref> Few days later EU closed its external borders.<ref name=\"schengen\">{{cite web | url=https://www.consilium.europa.eu/en/meetings/european-council/2020/03/17/ |title = Video conference of the members of the European Council, 17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Countries and territories implementing a global travel ban ==\n=== Asia ===\n*{{flag|Azerbaijan}}: Effective March 23, 2020, passengers are not allowed to enter Azerbaijan except passengers with a work permit and passengers with a special permission issued by the government of Azerbaijan.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://restrictions.info/news/detail/3010 | title=Azerbaijan - restriction update 23.03.2020 02:06 UTC: COVID-19 Travel Restrictions Database}}</ref>\n*{{flag|Armenia}}: Passengers are not allowed to enter Armenia until 14 May 2020.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://restrictions.info/news/detail/4219 | title=Armenia - restriction update 17.04.2020 12:00 UTC: COVID-19 Travel Restrictions Database}}</ref>\n*{{flag|Brunei}}: Effective 24 March 2020, all foreigners are not allowed to enter Brunei on all border checkpoints, including those on transit purposes.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://thescoop.co/2020/03/13/covid-19-live-updates/ |title = COVID-19 live updates: Tally climbs to 114 with 5 new infections|date = 13 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.brudirect.com/news.php?id=89853 |title=Minister Of Home Affairs Explained The Control Of Foreigner's Entry Into The Country |publisher=Brudirect.com |date= |accessdate=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n*{{flag|Mainland China}}: Effective 28 March 2020, entry refused to all foreigners holding visas or residence permits still valid to the time of the announcement issued on 26 March. All specific visa regulations and entry by foreign nationals with [[APEC Business Travel Card]]s will also be suspended.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fmprc.gov.cn/mfa_eng/wjbxw/t1761867.shtml|title=Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the People's Republic of China, National Immigration Administration Announcement on the Temporary Suspension of Entry by Foreign Nationals Holding Valid Chinese Visas or Residence Permits|publisher=Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the People's Republic of China|date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n*{{flag|Cyprus}}: The Cypriot government has announced that only its citizens, along with other Europeans working on the island and people with special permits will be allowed into the country for a 15-day period beginning on March 15.<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/live/world-51866403 As it happened- Coronavirus on Friday, 19:55 13 March 2020- Cyprus limits entry to country] ''/www.bbc.com'', accessed 15 March 2020</ref> This ban has been extended until 30 April 2020.<ref>[https://ec.europa.eu/transport/coronavirus-response_en European Union Department for Mobility and Transport on Coronavirus Response] accessed 13 April 2020</ref>\n*{{Flag|Georgia}}: The Georgian government imposed a ban on all foreign citizens entering the country and closed its borders. Georgia also halted all air travel with other countries on March 20. All restrictions end April 21.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.nytimes.com/reuters/2020/03/23/world/europe/23reuters-health-coronavirus-georgia.html|title=Georgia Bans Passenger Traffic on Domestic Railway Over Coronavirus|date=2020-03-23|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-05|url-status=live|agency=Reuters|publication-place=Tbilisi|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n*{{flag|Hong Kong}}: All non-Hong Kong residents who have been in overseas countries/territories (i.e. excluding mainland China, Macau and Taiwan) in the past 14 days are barred from entering Hong Kong, with exceptions provided for certain groups of non-Hong Kong residents such as spouses and minor children of Hong Kong residents as well as Macao residents who are registered under the Macao scheme under agreement between the Macau and the Hong Kong Government, and passengers are no longer allowed to transit through [[Hong Kong International Airport]] until further notice starting from 25 March 2020. Non-Hong Kong residents arriving from mainland China, Macau and Taiwan who have not been in any overseas countries/territories in the past 14 days are exempted from the ban, but they are still subject to compulsory quarantine for 14 days same as all other arrivals to Hong Kong.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.info.gov.hk/gia/general/202003/24/P2020032400050.htm |title = Government announces enhancements to anti-epidemic measures in four aspects}}</ref>\n*{{flag|India}}: Flights to India are suspended from 00:01 GMT 22 March 2020 until 18:30 GMT 14 April 2020. This does not apply to flights that carry goods for trade or essential goods and supplies, and their crew members, helpers, cleaners etc.\n*{{flag|Indonesia}}: Effective 1 April 2020, all foreigners (except residents, family connection, medical personnel, and people responsible for transport of goods) are not allowed to enter Indonesia on all border checkpoints, including those on transit purposes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnnindonesia.com/nasional/20200331210804-20-488901/larangan-wna-masuk-indonesia-berlaku-2-april |title=Larangan WNA Masuk Indonesia Berlaku 2 April |publisher=cnnindonesia.com |date= |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n*{{flag|Israel}}: Effective 12 March 2020, foreign travellers from any country are denied entry, unless a specific permit is given by the Foreign Ministry and the person can prove the ability to remain under home isolation for 14 days. Israeli citizens and permanents residents are required to enter 14-day home isolation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://govextra.gov.il/ministry-of-health/corona/corona-virus-en/|title=The Novel Coronavirus - Israel Ministry of Health|website=corona-virus}}</ref>\n*{{flag|Jordan}}: Effective 17 March 2020, Jordan will stop all incoming and outgoing passenger flights into the country.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/health-coronavirus-jordan-idUSL8N2B70IT|title=Jordan tightens lockdown to combat coronavirus|date=2020-03-14|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-03-15|language=en}}</ref>\n*{{flag|Laos}}: Flights to Lao People's Dem. Rep. are suspended until 3 May 2020.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://restrictions.info/news/detail/4223 | title=Lao People's Dem. Rep. - restriction update 17.04.2020 16:28 UTC: COVID-19 Travel Restrictions Database}}</ref>\n*{{flag|Macau}}: Effective 19 March 2020, all non-residents are prohibited to enter, except residents of mainland China, of Hong Kong and of Taiwan.<ref>{{cite web |title=Macao to ban overseas travellers in effort further to control COVID-19 locally |url=https://www.gov.mo/en/news/123607/ |website=Macao SAR Government Portal |accessdate=19 March 2020|date=17 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Macao to ban re-entry of any registered foreign non-resident workers, after stroke of midnight Thursday |url=https://www.gov.mo/en/news/123706/ |website=Macao SAR Government Portal |accessdate=19 March 2020 |date=18 March 2020}}</ref> On 5 April 2020, the Macanese government has announced the closure of the [[Hong Kong\u2013Zhuhai\u2013Macau Bridge]] which means all public transportation between Macao and Hong Kong has been suspended;<ref name=\"Macau News HKZMB\">{{cite web |title=MHong Kong-Macau delta bridge bus link suspended over COVID-19 threat (Update) |url=https://macaunews.mo/hong-kong-macau-delta-bridge-bus-link-suspended-over-covid-19-threat-update/ |website=Macao News |accessdate=5 April 2020 |date=5 April 2020}}</ref> only dual licence plate (HK/Macau) and freight vehicles are allowed to use the bridge.<ref name=\"Macau News HKZMB\" />\n*{{flag|Malaysia}}: All citizens are [[2020 Malaysia movement control order|prohibited]] from leaving the country while foreigners are prohibited from entering the country effective March 18, 2020. Airports and airspace remain open.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/malaysia-to-impose-lockdown-from-wednesday-to-march-31|title=Malaysia to impose lockdown from Wednesday to March 31|date=March 17, 2020|website=Straits Times}}</ref>\n*{{flag|Myanmar}}: All flights to Myanmar are suspended until 30 April 2020.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://restrictions.info/news/detail/4123 | title=Myanmar - restriction update 12.04.2020 11:02 UTC: COVID-19 Travel Restrictions Database}}</ref>\n*{{flag|Nepal}}: All international flights to Nepal are suspended until 30 April 2020.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://restrictions.info/news/detail/4054 | title=Nepal - restriction update 08.04.2020 16:48 UTC: COVID-19 Travel Restrictions Database}}</ref>\n*{{flag|North Korea}}: Closed its borders to all international tourists on January 21, 2020, one of the first countries to do so. Chinese visitors make up the bulk of foreign tourists to North Korea.<ref name=\"20200121reuters\" /> Also tightened/closed their border with mainland China.<ref name=\"newsweek1484978\" />\n*{{flag|Oman}}: Suspended tourist visas for all visitors, effective March 15, 2020, for 1 month.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfbusiness.com/oman-suspends-tourist-visas-halts-sports-activities-for-month/|title=Oman suspends tourist visas, halts sports activities for month|date=March 12, 2020|website=Gulf Business}}</ref> Moreover, all cruise ships will be prevented from entering Omani ports [https://www.omanonlinevisa.com/restricted-entry-to-oman/ for 1 month].\n*{{flag|Pakistan}}: Closed its airports for both arrivals and departures on 21 March 2020 for two weeks. The date was later postponed to 11 April 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/coronavirus-travel-restrictions-border-shutdowns-country-200318091505922.html|title=Coronavirus: Travel restrictions, border shutdowns by country|date=April 5, 2020|website=Al Jazeera}}</ref>\n*{{flag|Palestine}}: Tourist ban of West Bank from March 5, 2020 for 14 days.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.france24.com/en/20200305-palestinians-announce-west-bank-tourism-ban-over-coronavirus|title=Palestinians announce West Bank tourism ban over coronavirus|date=March 5, 2020|website=France 24}}</ref>\n*{{flag|Philippines}}: Visa issuance and visa-free entry for all foreign nationals are temporarily suspended as of March 19, 2020.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://globalnation.inquirer.net/186199/fwd-ph-temporarily-suspends-visa-issuance-visa-free-entry-of-all-foreign-nationals/amp|title=PH temporarily suspends visa issuance, visa-free entry to all foreign nationals|date=March 19, 2020|work=Philippine Daily Inquirer}}</ref> On March 22, all foreign visitors are barred from entry, with exceptions for foreign spouses and children of Filipino citizens, diplomatic officials, and workers for international organizations.<ref>{{cite web |title=Press Release: BI to implement DFA circular on suspension of arrivals |url=http://immigration.gov.ph/images/News/2020_Yr/03_Mar/2020Mar20b_Press.pdf |publisher=Bureau of Immigration |location=Philippines |format=PDF |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Cordero |first1=Ted |title=Foreigners banned from entering Philippines starting March 22 \u2013 DOTr |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/730560/foreigners-banned-from-entering-philippines-starting-march-22-dotr/story/ |agency=GMA News |date=March 20, 2019}}</ref>\n*{{flag|Qatar}}: On March 15, Qatar said it would ban inbound flights, except for cargo and transit flights, starting from March 18. The entry ban does not apply to Qatari citizens. Nationals of Qatar are not allowed to exit the country.\n*{{flag|Russia}}: Borders closed to foreigners with some exceptions, effective March 18 and until May 1.<ref name=\"indepa9405131\" />\n*{{flag|Saudi Arabia}}: All international flights suspended, except in exceptional cases, for a period of two weeks, as of March 15, 2020.<ref>The Kingdom\u2019s government has decided to suspend international flights, except in exceptional cases for a period of two weeks, as of March 15 at 11:00.</ref> The Saudi Ministry of Foreign Affairs recently issued a statement announcing that all religious visits (Umrah) to the sacred Muslim sites of Mecca and Medina [https://www.saudiarabiavisa.com/entry-restrictions/ have to be cancelled or postponed for the time being].\n*{{flag|Singapore}}: All foreigners are prohibited to entry and transit starting from 23 March, 11.59pm. Only people working in essential services like healthcare services and transport will be allowed into Singapore during this time.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Toh |first1=Ting Wei |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/health/coronavirus-all-short-term-visitors-barred-from-entering-and-transiting-in |title=Coronavirus: All short-term visitors barred from entering and transiting in Singapore from Monday, 11.59pm |website=The Straits Times |access-date=22 March 2020 |date=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n*{{flag|Sri Lanka}}: Effective 8 April 2020, visas and ETAs issued by Sri Lanka have been invalidated.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://restrictions.info/news/detail/4056 | title=Sri Lanka - restriction update 08.04.2020 18:22 UTC: COVID-19 Travel Restrictions Database}}</ref> All airports in Sri Lanka are closed.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://restrictions.info/tr/country/lk/ | title=Travel restrictions of Sri Lanka: COVID-19 Travel Restrictions Database}}</ref>\n*{{flag|Taiwan}}: Effective 19 March, non-citizens are prohibited to enter unless specifically approved.<ref>{{cite web |script-title=zh:3\u67085\u65e5\u81f314\u65e5\u81ea\u6b50\u6d32\u5165\u5883\u6c11\